  "decision_notes": "The problem requires deriving a ratio between two specific temperatures (Unruh and de Sitter-modified) within the context of MOND (Modified Newtonian Dynamics) interpolation. This involves defining the acceleration-dependent temperature scales and calculating their ratio.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "unruh_temperature_derivation",
      "instructions": "Define the standard flat-space Unruh temperature T_U(a) as a function of acceleration 'a' and the Planck constant, Boltzmann constant, and speed of light. Express it in its simplest algebraic form."
    },
    {
      "label": "desitter_modified_temperature_derivation",
      "instructions": "Define the de Sitter-modified Unruh temperature T_dS(a). In the context of MOND interpolation, this involves the effective acceleration or the modified gravitational field. Determine the expression for T_dS(a) based on the relationship between the local acceleration 'a' and the cosmological constant or de Sitter horizon acceleration."
    },
    {
      "label": "mond_interpolation_function_analysis",
      "instructions": "Identify the specific MOND interpolation function (such as the simple, standard, or deep-MOND limit) typically used to relate the Newtonian acceleration to the modified acceleration in de Sitter space. Determine how this function modifies the effective acceleration used in the temperature calculation."
    },
    {
      "label": "ratio_calculation_and_algebraic_simplification",
      "instructions": "Using the expressions for T_U(a) and T_dS(a) provided by the previous helpers, calculate the ratio T_U(a) / T_dS(a). Simplify the expression to its most reduced algebraic form, ensuring all physical constants are accounted for."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the algebraic expression for the Unruh temperature and the de Sitter-modified temperature (incorporating the MOND interpolation) to compute the final ratio. Verify that the resulting expression matches the expected algebraic identity for the given physical framework."
}

